4. Methods
Specifically, it will follow these steps:



Theory
Specify the assumptions of interest based on relevant literature;
Estimand
Define the estimands of interest;
Theory \(\rightarrow\) Design
Simulate a synthetic conceptual population grounded in the CJ structure and assumptions of interest;
Design \(\rightarrow\) Sample
Generate two synthetic samples and comparison datasets from the conceptual population in step \(3\);
{Theory, Design, Estimand} \(\rightarrow\) Estimator
Specify models for analyzing the first synthetic comparison dataset using both the classical BTL analysis and the Information-Theoretical model for CJ;
Estimator \(\rightarrow\) Prior predictive
Perform prior predictive checks;

4. Methods



{Estimator, Sample} \(\rightarrow\) Estimates
Apply both the classical BTL model and the Information-Theoretical model for CJ to the first synthetic comparison dataset;
Estimates \(\rightarrow\) {Diagnostic, Post predictive}
Assess the quality of the models and estimates in terms of convergence, parameter recovery, in-sample fit, out-of-sample fit, and in-sample predictive accuracy;
{Diagnostic, Post predictive} \(\rightarrow\) Estimator
Incrementally refine the model specified in step 5, repeating steps 5–9 until a sufficiently trustworthy model is obtained according to the criteria outlined in step 8;
Estimates \(\rightarrow\) Effects \(\leftarrow\) Estimand
Generate the estimates of interest for CJ the first synthetic comparison dataset using both the classical BTL analysis and the Information-Theoretical model, and interpret the results;
Estimates \(\rightarrow\) Predictions \(\leftarrow\) Estimand
Generate predictions for the second synthetic comparison dataset using both the classical BTL analysis and the Information-Theoretical model for CJ, and compare their out-of-sample predictive accuracy.

4.2 From Design to Sample
Differing only by replication seed, the study generates two synthetic samples and comparison datasets from the conceptual population.

For the sampling and comparison mechanisms illustrated in Figure 1 (\(S\) and \(C\), respectively) the study conducts sample size calculations (see next slides) and adopts the following design:


A sample of \(59\) individuals, divided into three groups: \(45\) normal-hearing (NH), \(7\) hearing-impaired with hearing aids (HI-HA), and \(7\) hearing-impaired with cochlear implants (HI-CI);
A sample of \(10\) stimuli per individual;
A sample of \(90\) judges, divided into three groups: \(10\) audiologist (AU), \(10\) primary teachers (PT), and \(25\) inexperienced listeners (IL);
Judges conduct only one-comparison of the same stimulus pair (i.e., not repeated measures design [25])
Stimuli is compared a total of \(20\) times across all judges.
